[2]
Date: Fri 4 Oct 2019
Source: Mountain Xpress [edited]
https://mountainx.com/blogwire/buncombe-county-issues-update-on-legionnaires-disease-outbreak/


Buncombe County Health & Human Services (HHS) continues to support the state investigation and sees these recent developments as a positive step towards understanding how this outbreak occurred. The outbreak has impacted many people in our community, and our thoughts are with all of those who are affected. Local health officials continue to investigate reports of illness related to the Legionnaires' disease outbreak, assist medical providers with case identification and proper lab testing, and collect and analyze data.

Here is the most recent news release from NCDHHS [North Carolina Department of Health & Human Services]: At this time, Buncombe County HHS is reporting 46 confirmed cases of Legionnaires' disease, including one fatality, as of 5 pm on [3 Oct 2019].

To check the status of the outbreak in WNC over the weekend, visit this link: https://epi.dph.ncdhhs.gov/cd/legionellosis/outbreak.html.

[County and confirmed cases as of 3 Oct 2019: Buncombe, 49; Burke, 2; Cherokee, 1; Gaston, 1; Granville, 1; Haywood, 10; Henderson, 33; Jackson, 1; Madison, 6; McDowell, 3; Mecklenburg, 3; Mitchell, 2; Polk, 1; Rutherford, 2; Transylvania, 3*; Union, 1; Watauga, 1; and Yancey, 1; out of state (SC), 7. Total: 128. Male, 73 (57%)**; female, 53 (41%)**. Median age in years (range), 61 (24-91)*. Hospitalizations, 81 (63%); deaths, 1. Legionnaires' disease, 120 (94%); Pontiac fever, 8 (6%). *Previously included suspect cases; **Some cases reported with unknown sex. - Mod.ML]

